Summary & Conclusions¶

Introduction¶

This project explores refund behavior in Indian e-commerce grocery delivery services, using a simulated dataset that captures real-world characteristics of platforms like Blinkit, Swiggy Instamart, and JioMart. The dataset includes detailed information such as:

  • Platform used
  • Delivery time and distance
  • Service rating
  • Product category
  • Order value, discount, and charges
  • Customer feedback
  • Refund request and delivery delay status

The primary objective is to build a supervised classification model in Phase 2 that can accurately predict whether a customer will request a refund for a given order.

Phase 1 Scope¶

In this initial phase, we focused on:

  • Cleaning and preprocessing the dataset (handling missing values, dropping ID-like columns, correcting time formats, etc.)
  • Feature engineering, including transformation of time values and binary encoding
  • Outlier detection and treatment for numerical columns like Order Value and Delivery Time
  • Generating statistical summaries and visualizations to understand patterns related to refund behavior

These tasks form the analytical groundwork for model development in Phase 2, where predictive techniques will be applied and evaluated.

Dataset Source¶

The dataset used in this project is publicly available on Kaggle, titled
E-Commerce Analytics: Swiggy, Zomato, Blinkit, published by LogicCraft by Himanshi.

It simulates real-world delivery patterns and customer behavior across major Indian quick-commerce platforms, including:

  • Swiggy Instamart
  • Blinkit
  • JioMart

The dataset is ideal for analyzing customer satisfaction, delivery performance, and refund behavior all of which align with the projects predictive goals.

Access Dataset on Kaggle

Dataset Details¶

The original dataset used in this project, titled Ecommerce_Delivery_Analytics.csv, consists of 100,000 rows and 11 features, simulating e-commerce delivery data from leading Indian quick-commerce platforms including Swiggy Instamart, JioMart, and Blinkit.

Each row represents a unique customer order, capturing key attributes such as:

  • Order time and platform
  • Product category and order value
  • Delivery time and distance
  • Customer feedback and service rating
  • Delivery delay and refund request status

To ensure efficient computation while maintaining statistical integrity, a random sample of 5,000 rows was selected for analysis. This sample preserves the original data's diversity and distribution, making it suitable for exploratory analysis and predictive modeling.

Dataset Features¶

In accordance with the project guidelines, the feature table below includes only those variables that are relevant for analysis and predictive modeling in Phase 2.

Features such as Order ID and Customer ID were intentionally excluded, as they are ID-like columns that serve only as unique identifiers and offer no predictive value. These were dropped during the data cleaning process.

The final set of features was selected based on their business relevance and potential influence on refund behavior, including operational metrics (e.g., delivery time), customer responses (e.g., service rating), and order-level details (e.g., order value, platform, category).

This refined subset forms the basis for both exploratory analysis in Phase 1 and model training in Phase 2.

Target Feature¶

The target variable for this project is Refund Requested, which indicates whether a customer requested a refund for a specific order.

This is a binary categorical variable, with the following values:

  • 1 Refund was requested (Yes)
  • 0 No refund was requested (No)

This feature acts as the output variable for the binary classification model to be developed in Phase 2. The objective is to use relevant input features (such as delivery performance, order value, and service rating) to predict the likelihood of a refund request, enabling proactive interventions to minimize refund-related losses.

Goals and Objectives¶

The overall goal of this project is to develop a machine learning model that can accurately predict whether a customer will request a refund, using data available at the time of order and delivery. This has significant real-world value for e-commerce platforms, as refund requests often reflect customer dissatisfaction, delivery issues, and potential financial losses.

Phase 1 Objectives – Data Exploration & Preparation¶

The focus of Phase 1 is to lay a solid foundation for predictive modeling by:

  • Conducting comprehensive data cleaning and preprocessing (handling missing values, correcting data types, and treating outliers)
  • Performing exploratory data analysis (EDA) to uncover trends, relationships, and anomalies
  • Encoding features appropriately and identifying those most relevant for prediction
  • Creating informative visualizations that highlight key patterns (e.g., refund behavior by platform or product category)
  • Preparing a clean and well-structured dataset for model development in Phase 2

Phase 2 Objectives – Predictive Modeling¶

The upcoming Phase 2 will focus on building and evaluating classification models to:

  • Identify the key drivers influencing refund behavior (e.g., delivery delay, service rating, order value)
  • Evaluate and compare multiple machine learning models using appropriate metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score
  • Build a model that is both predictively strong and interpretable, suitable for real-time deployment in customer service systems
  • Deliver actionable business insights to help e-commerce platforms reduce refund rates and enhance overall customer experience

Literature Review: Refund Prediction in E-Commerce using Machine Learning¶

In the fast-evolving landscape of e-commerce, refund prediction has become increasingly important due to its direct connection with customer satisfaction, financial performance, and operational efficiency. The application of machine learning to forecast refund requests can enable businesses to proactively mitigate customer dissatisfaction, improve logistics, and reduce the costs associated with returns and complaints. This literature review explores recent studies and developments in this domain, focusing on the intersection of machine learning, customer behavior analysis, and refund modeling in online retail.

E-commerce and Customer Return Behavior¶

Customer refund behavior has been studied extensively in e-commerce literature. A key insight comes from the work of Hong et al. (2020), who demonstrated how customer transaction history, delivery times, and satisfaction ratings can predict returns with high accuracy. They used logistic regression and decision tree classifiers on historical return datasets and found that late delivery, poor packaging, and mismatch between product description and reality are strong indicators of refund probability.

Importance of Delivery Performance¶

Delivery delays are one of the most cited reasons for refunds and dissatisfaction. Research by Lee & Yu (2019) found that integrating delivery performance metrics (e.g., on-time delivery, delivery distance, service rating) into predictive models significantly improves refund forecasting accuracy. Their model combined Support Vector Machines (SVM) with Random Forests and achieved over 80% accuracy on a large Korean e-commerce dataset.

Sentiment Analysis and Customer Feedback¶

Another influential study by Medhat et al. (2014) reviewed the effectiveness of sentiment analysis in predicting product return behavior. Analyzing customer feedback through Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques provides valuable insights into dissatisfaction that may not be visible through numerical ratings. Modern techniques such as BERT and LSTM-based models have shown promising results in classifying refund-intent through customer reviews.

Machine Learning Algorithms for Classification¶

Recent comparative studies have explored different algorithms for classification tasks involving binary outcomes such as refunds. For example, Wang et al. (2021) evaluated several supervised learning techniquesRandom Forest, XGBoost, Logistic Regression, and Neural Networkson Alibaba's e-commerce return dataset. XGBoost outperformed others in precision and recall due to its ability to capture non-linear interactions between features like payment method, product category, and delivery duration.

Data Challenges in Refund Prediction¶

Refund prediction in e-commerce faces persistent challenges related to data quality, class imbalance and limited labeled examples. Real world datasets are often skewed, with refund cases forming a small proportion, making accurate modeling difficult. He and Garcia (2009) highlight that such imbalance can cause classifiers to favour the majority class, overlooking critical refund cases. Buda et al (2018) further demonstrated that imbalance can reduce generalization in deep learning models. Noisy or incomplete transaction records also undermine model performance, as shown by Vatsalan et al (2013), who emphasized the risks of poor data linkage. In multiclass refund scenarios - e.g., by platform or product category - Wang and Yao (2013) note that imbalance intensifies, requiring more granular handling. To mitigate these issues, advanced techniques such as generative oversampling (Hayaeian Shrivan et al., 2025) and robust ensemble models like XGBoost (Chen & Guestrin, 2016) have been adopted. Yet, as Chen et al. (2024) observe, no single method universally solves imbalance, reinforcing the need for tailored approaches in refund modeling.

Feature Importance and Explainability¶

Interpreting model predictions is crucial for e-commerce managers. Ribeiro et al. (2016) introduced LIME (Local Interpretable Model-Agnostic Explanations), which allows understanding individual predictions, especially useful in refund prediction where human decisions still influence outcomes. Shapley values (SHAP) have also gained popularity in highlighting which features (e.g., discount applied, delivery charges) drive refund requests the most.

Domain-Specific Applications¶

In Indian e-commerce, where platforms like Swiggy Instamart, Blinkit, and JioMart dominate the quick-commerce segment, limited literature exists on refund prediction. However, Kumar et al. (2022) highlighted that Indian consumers are highly price-sensitive, and refund behavior is often tied to discount expectation, failed delivery promises, and product category. Their research using clustering and supervised models revealed that personal care and electronics had the highest refund rates.

Research Gap and Our Contribution¶

While existing studies have laid the foundation for refund prediction using ML, few studies explore refund forecasting in the context of Indian quick-commerce platforms with a combined emphasis on delivery time, service rating, and platform-specific dynamics. Our study contributes by applying machine learning techniques to simulate refund behavior in this domain using a real-world inspired dataset. We also integrate platform-wise and category-wise analysis with predictive modeling and visualization, creating a holistic view of refund tendencies in a rapidly growing market.

Outliers¶

In [19]:
#Handling Outliers with clamp function
def clamp(series, lower_percentile=1, upper_percentile=99):
    lower = np.percentile(series, lower_percentile)
    upper = np.percentile(series, upper_percentile)
    print(f"{series.name} Clamping Outliers to Range: [{round(lower,2)} - {round(upper,2)}]")
    return np.clip(series, lower, upper)

numeric_cols = ['Delivery Time (Minutes)', 'Order Value (INR)', 'Service Rating']
for col in numeric_cols:
    df[col] = clamp(df[col])
    

Delivery Time (Minutes) Clamping Outliers to Range: [7.0 - 54.0]
Order Value (INR) Clamping Outliers to Range: [66.99 - 1903.01]
Service Rating Clamping Outliers to Range: [1.0 - 5.0]
In [20]:
#Checking for any values that are still outside the above ranges
clamp_bounds = {
    'Delivery Time (Minutes)': (7.0, 54.0),
    'Order Value (INR)': (66.99, 1903.01),
    'Service Rating': (1.0,5.0)
}
for col, (low,high) in clamp_bounds.items():
    below = df[df[col] < low].shape[0]
    above = df[df[col] > high].shape[0]
    print(f"{col}: Values < {low} = {below}, Values > {high} = {above}")

Delivery Time (Minutes): Values < 7.0 = 0, Values > 54.0 = 0
Order Value (INR): Values < 66.99 = 0, Values > 1903.01 = 50
Service Rating: Values < 1.0 = 0, Values > 5.0 = 0

Boxplot Interpretation¶

In [21]:
#Visual Check of outliers with boxplot
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#Loop through each numeric column
for col in numeric_cols:
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25) #Calculating whisker limits using IQR method
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3-Q1
    lower_whisker = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
    upper_whisker = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    
    actual_min = df[col].min() #Actual min and max values from data after clamping
    actual_max = df[col].max()
    
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,1.8)) #Plotting boxplot
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col])
    plt.title(
        f"Boxplot of {col} after Clamping\n"
        f"Whisker Limits: [{round(lower_whisker, 2)} - {round(upper_whisker, 2)}] | "
        f"Actual Range: [{round(actual_min, 2)} - {round(actual_max, 2)}]"
    )
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

The boxplots generated for Order Value (INR) and Service Rating offer important insights into data distribution and outliers, especially after applying percentile-based clamping:

  • For Order Value (INR):

    • Although the calculated lower whisker limit was -454.4, no actual data points fell below the clamped minimum of 66.99. Therefore, the boxplot whisker starts at 66.99 consistent with standard boxplot behavior, which does not extend whiskers beyond observed values.
    • The maximum value of 1903.01, while within the clamped range, is still flagged as an outlier, because it lies beyond the calculated upper whisker (Q3 + 1.5 IQR). This is expected behavior in IQR-based outlier detection.

  • For Service Rating:

    • The theoretical upper whisker limit calculated from the IQR method was 9.5, but the actual maximum rating in the dataset is 5.0. Therefore, the whisker visually stops at 5.0 with no outliers displayed, which is standard when actual values do not exceed statistical thresholds.

These nuances reinforce the importance of understanding the difference between clamping thresholds and statistical outlier detection, especially when preparing data for machine learning models.

The histogram illustrates the distribution of order values across all transactions. A clear concentration of orders is observed between 200 and 600, reflecting the typical spending range in quick-commerce. The maximum order value, 1903.01, indicates a few high-value purchases, while the minimum, 66.99, marks the lower bound after outlier clamping. The KDE curve confirms a right-skewed distribution, highlighting that high-value orders are relatively rare.

The accompanying boxplot provides a statistical summary of the same distribution. The interquartile range (IQR) spans approximately 491, from Q1 = 282 to Q3 = 773, with a median order value of 474.5. The extended right whisker and the presence of outliers further reinforce the positive skew, suggesting that although most orders are moderately priced, a small number of significantly higher-value transactions extend the upper range.

These plots not only help in understanding user purchasing patterns but also assist in identifying potential outlier behavior that could influence predictive modeling.

In [28]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Recalculate refund rate per platform
refund_rate = df_cleaned.groupby('Platform')['Refund Requested'].mean().reset_index()
refund_rate['Refund Requested'] *= 100  # Convert to percentage
refund_rate = refund_rate.sort_values(by='Refund Requested', ascending=False)  # Sort descending

# Plot with detailed styling
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))
ax = sns.barplot(
    x='Platform',
    y='Refund Requested',
    data=refund_rate,
    color ='purple',
    edgecolor='black'
)

# Add text labels on top of each bar
for index, row in refund_rate.iterrows():
    ax.text(index, row['Refund Requested'] + 1, f"{row['Refund Requested']:.1f}%", 
            color='black', ha='center', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')

# Enhancing titles and labels
plt.title('Average Refund Rate by Platform (%)', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Platform', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Refund Rate (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylim(0, refund_rate['Refund Requested'].max() + 10)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This bar plot shows the percentage of orders that resulted in a refund request, grouped by platform. The refund rate is computed as:

Refund Rate (%) = (Refund Requested Orders / Total Orders) 100

  • Blinkit and JioMart both have a refund rate of 45.1%
  • Swiggy Instamart follows closely with 44.5%

Although the differences are small, the overall refund rates (~45%) indicate that nearly half of all orders lead to a refund request, which can have serious cost implications for the business.

Business Insight:

  • Reducing refund rates, even slightly, can lead to major savings and improved customer satisfaction.
  • Platforms should investigate common refund triggers (e.g. delivery delays, product issues) and take proactive actions.

3. Delivery Time by Product Category and Refund Requested¶

In [33]:
# Set the refund palette
refund_palette = {0: '#4CAF50', 1: '#F44336'}  # Green for No, Red for Yes

# Create the boxplot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

ax = sns.boxplot(
    data=df,
    x='Product Category',
    y='Delivery Time (Minutes)',
    hue='Refund Requested',
    palette=refund_palette,
    linewidth=1.2,
    fliersize=3
)

# Calculate and annotate IQR for each category/refund combo
categories = df['Product Category'].unique()
for i, category in enumerate(categories):
    for refund in [0, 1]:
        subset = df[(df['Product Category'] == category) & (df['Refund Requested'] == refund)]
        if not subset.empty:
            q1 = subset['Delivery Time (Minutes)'].quantile(0.25)
            q3 = subset['Delivery Time (Minutes)'].quantile(0.75)
            iqr = q3 - q1
            x_pos = i + (-0.2 if refund == 0 else 0.2)

            # Annotate IQR with arrow
            ax.annotate(f"IQR={iqr:.1f}",
                        xy=(x_pos, q3 + 1),
                        xytext=(x_pos - 0.3, q3 + 6),
                        arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->', color='black'),
                        ha='center', fontsize=9, color='black')

# Customize labels and title
plt.title('Delivery Time by Product Category and Refund Requested', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', color='#333333')
plt.xlabel('Product Category', fontsize=14, fontweight='semibold')
plt.ylabel('Delivery Time (Minutes)', fontsize=14, fontweight='semibold')
plt.xticks(rotation=30, fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)

# Adjust and relabel legend to bottom center outside
handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
labels = ['No', 'Yes']
legend = plt.legend(handles=handles, labels=labels, title='Refund Requested', loc='lower center',
                    bbox_to_anchor=(0.8, -0.25), ncol=2, frameon=True)
plt.setp(legend.get_title(), fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.setp(legend.get_texts(), fontsize=12)

plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This boxplot compares delivery time distributions across different product categories, segmented by whether a refund was requested. It also annotates the interquartile range (IQR) for each group.

Key Insights:¶

  • The IQRs are relatively consistent across all product categories (~11 to 14 minutes), suggesting uniform delivery performance variability.
  • Refunds (in red) tend to have similar or slightly lower median delivery times than non-refunded orders, indicating delivery delay alone may not be the primary refund driver.
  • Despite similar delivery performance, some categories like Dairy and Snacks still experience high refund volumes, hinting at potential issues in product quality or customer expectations.

Business Relevance:¶

  • This plot helps isolate whether delivery duration is a key driver for refunds across product lines.
  • Uniform IQRs suggest that operational consistency exists; however, attention may be needed in category-specific quality control or communication post-delivery.

Correlation Heatmap of Numeric Features¶

In [34]:
# Select only numeric columns
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

# Compute correlation matrix
corr_matrix = numeric_df.corr()

# Plot heatmap with improved aesthetics
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.set(style="white")

# Define a more visually appealing diverging colormap
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 20, as_cmap=True)

# Create the heatmap
heatmap = sns.heatmap(
    corr_matrix,
    annot=True,
    fmt=".2f",
    cmap=cmap,
    center=0,
    linewidths=0.7,
    square=True,
    cbar_kws={"shrink": .85, "label": "Correlation Coefficient"},
    annot_kws={"size": 11, "weight": "bold"}
)

# Aesthetic titles and layout
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Numeric Features', fontsize=18, weight='bold', color='#333333')
plt.xticks(rotation=30, fontsize=11)
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This heatmap displays the pairwise Pearson correlation coefficients between all numerical features in the dataset, including delivery time, service rating, order value, delivery delay, and refund status.

Key Observations:¶

  • Service Rating and Refund Requested show a strong negative correlation (-0.91), indicating that lower service ratings are strongly associated with higher refund requests. This aligns with intuitive business logic dissatisfied customers are more likely to request refunds.
  • Delivery Delay and Delivery Time exhibit a moderate positive correlation (0.64), validating that longer deliveries are more likely to be flagged as delayed an expected operational insight.
  • Refund Requested and Delivery Delay show a weak negative correlation (-0.03), suggesting that delivery delays may not be the primary factor influencing refund behavior.
  • Order Value has almost no correlation with refunds or delivery performance, implying that customers' decision to refund is not strongly price-dependent.

Business Relevance:¶

  • These correlations help identify which factors influence refund behavior the most, providing guidance for feature selection in predictive modeling (Phase 2).
  • The strong inverse link between service rating and refunds highlights the need for customer service improvements.
  • Weak correlations among other variables suggest that a multivariate analysis (e.g., classification modeling) is necessary to capture the full complexity of refund drivers.

Summary & Conclusions¶

In Phase 1 of our project, we explored refund behavior in the Indian e-commerce industry using a real-world inspired dataset sourced from Kaggle. Our primary objective was to prepare the data for predictive modeling by performing data cleaning, preprocessing, and exploratory data analysis (EDA).

Key Steps:¶

  • Data Cleaning & Preprocessing

    • Handled missing values and removed ID-like columns (e.g., Order ID, Customer ID).
    • Converted time-based features into numeric format.
    • Encoded binary variables (e.g., 'Yes' to 1, 'No' to 0).
    • Used percentile-based clamping to treat outliers in key numeric variables.

  • Data Exploration & Visualization

    • Plotted a total of 11 visualizations across:
      • One-variable plots (Histogram, Boxplots, Count Plots) (4 nos)
      • Two-variable plots (Refund vs Platform, Rating vs Refund, Category vs Refund) (3 nos)
      • Three-variable plots (e.g., Platform vs Product Category vs Refunds) (3 nos)
      • Correlation Heatmap of Numeric Features (1 nos)

Key Insights:¶

  • The majority of orders are priced between 200600, and most deliveries happen around 30 minutes, suggesting efficient delivery but price-sensitive customers.
  • Swiggy Instamart showed the highest refund rate, followed by Blinkit and JioMart.
  • Refunds were most frequent in Personal Care and Snacks & Beverages, suggesting these categories may be more prone to dissatisfaction or issues.
  • Surprisingly, many refunds occurred even when 5-star service ratings were given, highlighting potential hidden factors such as product quality or misalignment in expectations.
  • Delivery delays were moderately associated with refund requests, but not always a definitive indicator.

Next Steps (Phase 2 Preview):¶

With a clean and well-understood dataset, we are now ready to move into Phase 2, where we will:

  • Build and evaluate supervised machine learning models to predict refund requests.
  • Perform feature selection, model tuning, and comparison across classification algorithms.
  • Derive actionable insights to help platforms reduce refund rates and improve customer satisfaction.
